What can you infer from these plots? Don’t just explain what’s in the graph, but speculate or tell a short story (1-2 paragraphs max).

We can see significant differences in alcohol consumption over three classes of alcohol: beer, wine, and spirits. This comes along with at least two reasons behind it:

First, culture and secondly wealth. For beer consumption we see that Namibia has the highest as it used to be a German colony, Czech Republic with the City of Pilsen (founding place for the beer type: “Pils”) has the second highest beer consumption, and Germany has the 4th highest beer consumption with its long history of beer making and currently more than 1,500 beer breweries all over Germany. What is more, we see that muslim countries are not included in the top alcohol consuming countries, as their religion and culture is against alcohol. For the wealth we can see that a lot of rich western countries have a higher consumption as they have more money to spend on luxury goods, i.e. alcohol. - Type of alcohol depending on - German history , had a lot of wheat, started to produce beer …b gfdg - sterotypes (France: wine, Germany: beer, spirit: Russia, Belarus)

First, culture and secondly wealth. For beer consumption we see that Namibia has the highest as it used to be a German colony, the Czech Republic with the City of Pilsen (founding place for the beer type: “Pils”) has the second highest beer consumption, and Germany has the 4th highest beer consumption with its long history of beer making and currently more than 1,500 beer breweries all over Germany. The origins of particular alcohol consumption may lay in the can be connected to the economic resources available to a country during its development. For example, Germany had a prosperous agriculture industry with a big production of wheat. As a result, this allowed them to start successful beer production, making this drink popular among the citizens. At the same time, the interesting fact is that well-known stereotypes are actually reflected in the data. Countries like Russia and Belarus indeed consume the highest amount of spirits, especially, we believe, their famous vodka. Germany and the Czech Republic are leading in beer consumption, while France and Portugal stick to their prominent wines. What is more, we see that Muslim countries are not included in the top alcohol consuming countries, as their religion and culture is against alcohol. For wealth, we can see that a lot of rich western countries have a higher consumption as they have more money to spend on luxury goods, i.e. alcohol. Lastly, another interesting observation is that there are no countries with leading positions in several categories like beer and spirits, or wine and spirits. This means, that the actual alcohol consumption is more about preferences of the citizens connected to the above-stated reasons, rather than just pure consumption of alcohol with an aim to get tipsy.

2 Analysis of movies- IMDB dataset

We will look at a subset sample of movies, taken from the Kaggle IMDB 5000 movie dataset

movies <- vroom::vroom("movies.csv")
glimpse(movies)

Besides the obvious variables of title, genre, director, year, and duration, the rest of the variables are as follows:

  • gross : The gross earnings in the US box office, not adjusted for inflation
  • budget: The movie’s budget
  • cast_facebook_likes: the number of facebook likes cast memebrs received
  • votes: the number of people who voted for (or rated) the movie in IMDB
  • reviews: the number of reviews for that movie
  • rating: IMDB average rating

  • Examine the relationship between gross and rating. Produce a scatterplot, faceted by genre and discuss whether IMDB ratings are likely to be a good predictor of how much money a movie will make at the box office. Is there anything strange in this dataset?

For most genres, the higher the ratings are, the more gross revenue a movie will make at the box office.

In some genres there is even a negative correlation, i.e. Documentary. However, for the genres with many data points, i.e. Action, Adventure, Commedy, Crime, Drama, we can see a slightly positive correlation between the ratings and the money spend in box offices. However, animation, documentary, fantasy and sci-fi are exceptions. For family, romance, musical, thriller and western, the data is not sufficient to tell any relationships. The dataset is biased towards certain genres of movies, and it fail to represent the complete landscape of the movie industry.

Next, let’s choose the Dow Jones Industrial Aveareg (DJIA) stocks and their ticker symbols and download some data. Besides the thirty stocks that make up the DJIA, we will also add SPY which is an SP500 ETF (Exchange Traded Fund).

djia_url <- "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dow_Jones_Industrial_Average"

#get tables that exist on URL
tables <- djia_url %>% 
  read_html() %>% 
  html_nodes(css="table")


# parse HTML tables into a dataframe called djia. 
# Use purr::map() to create a list of all tables in URL
djia <- map(tables, . %>% 
               html_table(fill=TRUE)%>% 
               clean_names())


# constituents
table1 <- djia[[2]] %>% # the second table on the page contains the ticker symbols
  mutate(date_added = ymd(date_added),
         
         # if a stock is listed on NYSE, its symbol is, e.g., NYSE: MMM
         # We will get prices from yahoo finance which requires just the ticker
         
         # if symbol contains "NYSE*", the * being a wildcard
         # then we jsut drop the first 6 characters in that string
         ticker = ifelse(str_detect(symbol, "NYSE*"),
                          str_sub(symbol,7,11),
                          symbol)
         )

# we need a vector of strings with just the 30 tickers + SPY
tickers <- table1 %>% 
  select(ticker) %>% 
  pull() %>% # pull() gets them as a sting of characters
  c("SPY") # and lets us add SPY, the SP500 ETF
# Notice the cache=TRUE argument in the chunk options. Because getting data is time consuming, # cache=TRUE means that once it downloads data, the chunk will not run again next time you knit your Rmd

myStocks <- tickers %>% 
  tq_get(get  = "stock.prices",
         from = "2000-01-01",
         to   = "2020-08-31") %>%
  group_by(symbol)

Financial performance analysis depend on returns; If I buy a stock today for 100 and I sell it tomorrow for 101.75, my one-day return, assuming no transaction costs, is 1.75%. So given the adjusted closing prices, our first step is to calculate daily and monthly returns.

#calculate daily returns
myStocks_returns_daily <- myStocks %>%
  tq_transmute(select     = adjusted, 
               mutate_fun = periodReturn, 
               period     = "daily", 
               type       = "log",
               col_rename = "daily_returns",
               cols = c(nested.col))  

#calculate monthly  returns
myStocks_returns_monthly <- myStocks %>%
  tq_transmute(select     = adjusted, 
               mutate_fun = periodReturn, 
               period     = "monthly", 
               type       = "arithmetic",
               col_rename = "monthly_returns",
               cols = c(nested.col)) 

#calculate yearly returns
myStocks_returns_annual <- myStocks %>%
  group_by(symbol) %>%
  tq_transmute(select     = adjusted, 
               mutate_fun = periodReturn, 
               period     = "yearly", 
               type       = "arithmetic",
               col_rename = "yearly_returns",
               cols = c(nested.col))

Create a dataframe and assign it to a new object, where you summarise monthly returns since 2017-01-01 for each of the stocks and SPY; min, max, median, mean, SD.

summarise_monthly_returns <- myStocks_returns_monthly %>%
  group_by(symbol)%>%
  summarise(min_month_return = min(monthly_returns), 
            max_month_return = max(monthly_returns),
            median_month_return = median(monthly_returns),
            mean_month_return = mean(monthly_returns),
            sd_month_return = sd(monthly_returns)
            )

Plot a density plot, using geom_density(), for each of the stocks

ggplot(myStocks_returns_monthly, aes(x=monthly_returns))+
  geom_density()+
  facet_wrap(~symbol)+
  labs(title='Monthly Returns - Density Plots\n', x="\nMonthly returns", y="Percentage\n")+
  theme_economist()

What can you infer from this plot? Which stock is the riskiest? The least risky?

We can see that the stocks densities seem to have a standard normal distribution. The stocks with the widest density plots have the most volatility present. The riskiest stock form what we can see in the graphs seems to be AXP and the least risky AAPL

Finally, produce a plot that shows the expected monthly return (mean) of a stock on the Y axis and the risk (standard deviation) in the X-axis. Please use ggrepel::geom_text_repel() to label each stock with its ticker symbol

library(ggrepel)

ggplot(summarise_monthly_returns, aes(y=mean_month_return, x=sd_month_return, label=symbol))+
  geom_point() +
  geom_text_repel()+
  geom_lm(method=lm,se=FALSE)+
  theme_economist()+
  labs(title="Relation between monthly return and risk\n", y="Monthly return", x="\nRisk (standard deviation)")

What can you infer from this plot? Are there any stocks which, while being riskier, do not have a higher expected return?

From the plot we can infer that as the mean monthly return rises, so does the standard deviation, which makes sense, since a higher return usually indicates higher variability in prices, meaning that the higher the return of the stock the more risk associated with the returns. There are some cases, where the volatility (standard deviation) is high, with a lower mean monthly return. In particular, the biggest outliar is DOW, with a mean monthly return smaller than 0.01 and the highest standard deviation. There are some other cases bordering on having outliar-like characteristics, like Cisco Systems, american express and other financial services stocks like JP Morgan and Goldman Sachs.

6 Challenge 2: 2016 California Contributors plots

# Make sure you use vroom() as it is significantly faster than read.csv()
library(patchwork)
library(tidytext)
CA_contributors_2016 <- vroom::vroom("CA_contributors_2016.csv")%>%
  mutate(zip = as.character(zip))

zip_codes <- vroom::vroom("zip_code_database.csv")%>%
  select(zip,primary_city)

top_candidates <- left_join(CA_contributors_2016,zip_codes)

top_candidates%>%
  group_by(cand_nm)%>%
  filter(cand_nm %in% c("Trump, Donald J.","Clinton, Hillary Rodham"))%>%
  group_by(cand_nm,primary_city)%>%
  summarise(city_donation=sum(contb_receipt_amt))%>%
  top_n(10)%>%
  mutate(cand_nm=as.factor(cand_nm), primary_city = reorder_within(primary_city,city_donation,cand_nm))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=city_donation, y=primary_city, fill=cand_nm))+
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE)+
  facet_wrap(~cand_nm,scales = "free")+
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::dollar_format())+
  scale_y_reordered()+
  labs(x = "Amount raised",
         y = NULL,
         title = "Where did candidates raise most money?")

top10_cand_name <- top_candidates%>%
  group_by(cand_nm)%>%
  summarise(cand_donation=sum(contb_receipt_amt))%>%
  arrange(desc(cand_donation))%>%
  top_n(10)

top10_cand_city <- left_join(top10_cand_name,top_candidates,"cand_nm")%>%
  group_by(cand_nm,primary_city)%>%
  summarise(city_donation=sum(contb_receipt_amt))%>%
  top_n(10)%>%
  mutate(cand_nm=as.factor(cand_nm), primary_city = reorder_within(primary_city,city_donation,cand_nm))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=city_donation, y=primary_city, fill=cand_nm))+
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE)+
  facet_wrap(~cand_nm,scales = "free", nrow = 5)+
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::dollar_format())+
  scale_y_reordered()+
  labs(x = "Amount raised",
         y = NULL,
         title = "Where did candidates raise most money?",
       subtitle = "Top 10 candidates by money raised")
  
  top10_cand_city
